title.narrative: OUTPUT 4: NUTRITION POLICY & INSTITUTIONAL FRAMEWORKS

description.narrative: National Nutrition Policy and frameworks are aligned with international standards and monitored annually, which contributes to Communication And Advocacy, Cross Sectoral - Gender Discriminatory Roles And Practices, Cross-Sectoral - Human Rights, Cross-Sectoral - Other Programme Areas, Early Detection And Treatment Of Malnutrition, Health And Development In Early Childhood And Adolescence, Immunization Services As Part Of Primary Health Care, Mental Health And Psychosocial Well-Being, Nutrition In Early Childhood, Nutrition Of Adolescents And Women, Strengthening Primary Health Care And High-Impact Health Interventions, Strengthening Primary Health Care And High-Impact Health Interventions (Covid). UNICEF aims to achieve this through Data, Research, Evaluation And Knowledge Management, Evaluations, Research And Data, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2022, more children, adolescent girls and women of childbearing age access and utilize nutrition services, nutrient-rich foods and supplements to improve their well-being

description.narrative: Advocacy efforts by UNICEF for government to prioritize nutrition in the national development agenda continued to yield success.; Nutrition is now integrated in the Medium-Term Development Plan;(MTDP) and the Medium-Term Development Policy Framework (MTDPF) 2022-2025. ;Several significant policy actions aimed at improving the nutrition status of Ghanaian children were successfully supported by UNICEF, including the regulation of marketing of unhealthy foods, updating of the law that prohibits marketing of breastmilk substitutes and securing commitment for government to enact law that extends maternity leave from 12 weeks to 18 weeks. ; | Status:On-track | As-of Date:07/01/2022
